WEBVTT

00:00:00.000 --> 00:00:05.440
So today, I'll be talking about advances in the management of ALL.

00:00:05.840 --> 00:00:08.960
I'm going to focus on pH-negative B-cell ALL.

00:00:10.560 --> 00:00:14.840
So the question is, how can we improve outcomes in patients with ALL?

00:00:15.660 --> 00:00:21.020
In pediatric ALL, our five-year overall survival rates have been 90% or more.

00:00:21.940 --> 00:00:28.760
Unfortunately, in adults, this has been in the range of 20% to 80%, and this has depended

00:00:28.760 --> 00:00:33.640
on age, biology, as well as comorbidities of patients.

00:00:34.180 --> 00:00:36.480
And so novel approaches are clearly needed.

00:00:37.740 --> 00:00:45.720
So in terms of the treatment of young adults with ALL, one thing that has changed, many

00:00:45.720 --> 00:00:53.320
years ago, when I had just started at the clinic, this retrospective data came out and

00:00:53.320 --> 00:00:57.260
was published by both Wendy Stock and Nicholas Wazell.

00:00:57.520 --> 00:01:03.860
Showing that in young adults treated with pediatric regimens, these were retrospective

00:01:03.860 --> 00:01:10.300
studies, their outcome was much better when they were treated on pediatric cooperative

00:01:10.300 --> 00:01:13.640
group trials versus adult cooperative group trials.

00:01:13.640 --> 00:01:18.540
And there was a lot of controversy at that time about whether these patients should be

00:01:18.540 --> 00:01:20.160
treated by pediatricians.

00:01:20.880 --> 00:01:23.220
So this led to C10403.

00:01:23.220 --> 00:01:26.800
This was an adult cooperative group trial.

00:01:26.800 --> 00:01:26.880
This was an adult cooperative group trial.

00:01:26.880 --> 00:01:26.940
This was an adult cooperative group trial.

00:01:26.940 --> 00:01:27.060
This was an adult cooperative group trial.

00:01:27.060 --> 00:01:27.300
This was an adult cooperative group trial.

00:01:27.300 --> 00:01:27.360
This was an adult cooperative group trial.

00:01:27.360 --> 00:01:27.480
This was an adult cooperative group trial.

00:01:27.480 --> 00:01:27.500
This was an adult cooperative group trial.

00:01:27.500 --> 00:01:30.620
using a pediatric-based regimen.

00:01:30.620 --> 00:01:38.460
And based on this trial, I showed that we really could reach similar outcomes by using

00:01:38.460 --> 00:01:46.700
a pediatric-based regimen in these young adults with ALL.

00:01:46.700 --> 00:01:49.720
But older adults have still remained a problem.

00:01:49.720 --> 00:01:58.700
And so this is data from Wendy Stock showing the outcomes of patients enrolled on the CA-LGB

00:01:58.700 --> 00:02:00.760
cooperative group trials.

00:02:00.760 --> 00:02:06.060
And you can see that in these older patients that are 60 years of age and older, their

00:02:06.060 --> 00:02:09.160
outcome has really been quite poor.

00:02:09.160 --> 00:02:12.060
And this is probably for a number of reasons.

00:02:12.060 --> 00:02:18.140
Poor tolerance of chemotherapy and comorbidities.

00:02:18.140 --> 00:02:19.620
And also the biology.

00:02:19.620 --> 00:02:21.560
The biology of the disease.

00:02:21.560 --> 00:02:25.240
And so the question is, what can we do to help improve this?

00:02:25.240 --> 00:02:29.660
And this has really been a focus of many of the current clinical trials.

00:02:29.660 --> 00:02:34.040
And so the question has been, can we incorporate novel agents?

00:02:34.040 --> 00:02:38.860
Can we decrease the amount of traditional chemotherapy we give?

00:02:38.860 --> 00:02:45.900
And also, can we incorporate CAR-T therapy in the upfront setting?

00:02:45.900 --> 00:02:49.520
And so two of the agents that have been novel.

00:02:49.520 --> 00:02:52.460
They have been FDA-approved.

00:02:52.460 --> 00:03:00.460
Inotuzumab has been FDA-approved for relapsed refractory B-cell ALL based on the INOVATE

00:03:00.460 --> 00:03:07.220
trial, showing that it was superior to standard of care chemotherapy.

00:03:07.220 --> 00:03:15.900
Blinitumumab, which is the anti-CD19 bispecific T-cell engaging antibody, has been FDA-approved

00:03:15.900 --> 00:03:19.420
in both MRD-positive BALL and the T-cell engaging antibody.

00:03:19.420 --> 00:03:23.420
As well as relapsed refractory B-cell ALL.

00:03:23.420 --> 00:03:28.120
And so these agents now have been incorporated up front.

00:03:28.120 --> 00:03:32.800
And so probably one of the largest recent studies that has really changed our standard

00:03:32.800 --> 00:03:39.740
of care in the upfront treatment of patients with newly diagnosed B-cell ALL has been the

00:03:39.740 --> 00:03:41.440
E1910 trial.

00:03:41.440 --> 00:03:44.140
This was led by Mark Litzel.

00:03:44.140 --> 00:03:49.320
This trial looked at chemotherapy versus chemotherapy.

00:03:49.320 --> 00:03:53.780
Plus, Blinitumumab as post-remission treatment.

00:03:53.780 --> 00:04:00.060
And for the purposes of this specific trial, looked at Blinitumumab in post-remission treatment

00:04:00.060 --> 00:04:03.740
in those patients that were MRD-negative.

00:04:03.740 --> 00:04:11.500
And so this was presented at ASH and really is kind of astounding in that it showed an

00:04:11.500 --> 00:04:18.260
overall survival in those patients treated with Blinitumumab in frontline therapy and

00:04:18.260 --> 00:04:19.220
really has led to improvement.

00:04:19.220 --> 00:04:23.760
And so in this trial, we were able to do a standard of care change.

00:04:23.760 --> 00:04:30.180
Now, notably in those patients that are 55 years of age and older, there was not, again,

00:04:30.180 --> 00:04:35.460
this trial was not powered to look at that older age group, but there was not as much

00:04:35.460 --> 00:04:37.420
benefit in those patients.

00:04:37.420 --> 00:04:42.300
And so there still has been a question for those patients that are 55 or 60 years of

00:04:42.300 --> 00:04:47.720
age or older, what do we do to improve outcome?

00:04:47.720 --> 00:04:49.120
And so this is an older study.

00:04:49.120 --> 00:04:53.320
And so this is a study that was done in a study that was done in the U.S.

